          </div>
          <div class="tdg-box tdg-profile"><h4 class="tdg-boxtitle">Player Profile</h4><p class="tdg-profile-name">Judit Polgar</p><p class="tdg-profile-meta">Hungary · b. 1976 · Peak rating 2735</p><p class="tdg-boxtext">The strongest female chess player in history and the only woman ever to crack the world's top ten, reaching No. 8 in 2005. Trained from childhood by her father Laszlo in a famous experiment in early education, she skipped the women-only circuit entirely and made her name against the men. Over her career she defeated eleven players who held the world title, including Garry Kasparov, Magnus Carlsen, Anatoly Karpov, and Viswanathan Anand. She retired from competitive play in 2014 and now coaches and promotes chess in schools.</p><p class="tdg-cta"><a href="/daily/archive">More from the players desk &rarr;</a></p></div><div class="tdg-box tdg-archives"><h4 class="tdg-boxtitle">From the Archives</h4><figure class="tdg-archfig"><img class="tdg-archimg" src="https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/4/46/Paul_Morphy_1859_photo_portrait.jpg" alt="Paul Morphy, photographed in 1859" loading="lazy" /><figcaption class="tdg-archcap">Paul Morphy, photographed in 1859.</figcaption></figure><p class="tdg-profile-name">Paul Morphy</p><p class="tdg-profile-meta">New Orleans · 1837&ndash;1884 · The Pride and Sorrow of Chess</p><p class="tdg-boxtext">A century before Fischer, an American from New Orleans was the strongest player alive. Largely self-taught, Morphy crushed Europe&rsquo;s best on a single 1858 tour, grasping rapid development and open lines decades ahead of his time. He retired from chess at 22, never playing seriously again. His brief, brilliant career &mdash; and the quiet decline that followed &mdash; earned him the title &ldquo;the Pride and Sorrow of Chess.&rdquo;</p><p class="tdg-cta"><a href="/daily/archive">More chess history &rarr;</a></p></div><div class="tdg-box tdg-explainer">
            <h4 class="tdg-boxtitle">What Is a Gambit?</h4>
            <p class="tdg-boxtext">A gambit is a chess opening where a player deliberately sacrifices material — usually a pawn, sometimes more — in exchange for faster development, better piece activity, or an attack on the enemy king. The word comes from the Italian gambetto, meaning "a leg trip" or "a stumble," from gamba (leg). It first appeared in 1561 in a chess book by the Spanish priest Ruy López de Segura. In everyday English the word has grown well beyond chess — a "gambit" now describes any opening move in a conversation, negotiation, or political maneuver where you give up something small to gain something larger. Famous chess gambits include the King's Gambit, the Queen's Gambit, and the Evans Gambit.</p>
            <p class="tdg-cta"><a href="/chess-school/learn-to-play">Want to learn how to play? →</a></p>
