          <div class="tdg-rule"></div><article class="tdg-story"><p class="tdg-kicker">Opening Spotlight</p><h3 class="tdg-storyhead">The Sicilian Defence</h3><p class="tdg-body">Begun with 1.e4 c5, the Sicilian is the most popular and most analysed reply to White&rsquo;s king-pawn opening, favoured at every level from club play to the World Championship. Instead of mirroring White symmetrically, Black strikes at the centre from the side, accepting an unbalanced position in return for active, fighting chances. The resulting positions are sharp and double-edged, which is exactly why ambitious players reach for it when they need to win with the black pieces.</p><p class="tdg-body">Its many branches &mdash; the Najdorf, the Dragon, the Scheveningen, the Sveshnikov, and the Taimanov among them &mdash; each carry their own deep body of theory and their own devotees. Bobby Fischer and Garry Kasparov both leaned on the Najdorf in their title runs, and the opening remains a proving ground where preparation and nerve are tested in equal measure.</p></article>
        </section>


      </main>

      <section class="tdg-games" id="tdg-games"><div class="tdg-gameshead"><span class="tdg-pin">♞</span><h2 class="tdg-localtitle">Games of the Week</h2><span class="tdg-localtag">Annotated</span></div><p class="tdg-localintro">Two games worth replaying — one from the men's game, one from the women's — chosen for their beauty and their place in chess history. Set up a board and follow along.</p><div class="tdg-gamesgrid"><article class="tdg-game"><p class="tdg-kicker">Men · The Game of the Century</p><h3 class="tdg-storyhead">Donald Byrne – Bobby Fischer</h3><p class="tdg-game-meta">Rosenwald Trophy, New York 1956 · Grünfeld Defence · <strong>0–1</strong></p><p class="tdg-body">A 13-year-old Fischer unleashes 17…Be6!!, offering his queen to launch an unstoppable attack with his minor pieces — still the most famous queen sacrifice ever played by a child prodigy.</p><div class="tdg-moves"><p class="tdg-moves-title">Full Game</p><pre class="tdg-moves-pre">1.Nf3 Nf6 2.c4 g6 3.Nc3 Bg7 4.d4 O-O 5.Bf4 d5 6.Qb3 dxc4 7.Qxc4 c6 8.e4 Nbd7 9.Rd1 Nb6 10.Qc5 Bg4 11.Bg5 Na4 12.Qa3 Nxc3 13.bxc3 Nxe4 14.Bxe7 Qb6 15.Bc4 Nxc3 16.Bc5 Rfe8+ 17.Kf1 Be6 18.Bxb6 Bxc4+ 19.Kg1 Ne2+ 20.Kf1 Nxd4+ 21.Kg1 Ne2+ 22.Kf1 Nc3+ 23.Kg1 axb6 24.Qb4 Ra4 25.Qxb6 Nxd1 26.h3 Rxa2 27.Kh2 Nxf2 28.Re1 Rxe1 29.Qd8+ Bf8 30.Nxe1 Bd5 31.Nf3 Ne4 32.Qb8 b5 33.h4 h5 34.Ne5 Kg7 35.Kg1 Bc5+ 36.Kf1 Ng3+ 37.Ke1 Bb4+ 38.Kd1 Bb3+ 39.Kc1 Ne2+ 40.Kb1 Nc3+ 41.Kc1 Rc2# 0-1</pre></div></article><article class="tdg-game"><p class="tdg-kicker">Women · A Historic First</p><h3 class="tdg-storyhead">Judit Polgar – Garry Kasparov</h3><p class="tdg-game-meta">Russia vs. The Rest of the World, Moscow 2002 · Ruy Lopez · <strong>1–0</strong></p><p class="tdg-body">The day Judit Polgar became the first woman to beat a reigning world No. 1 in a classical game. A crisp Berlin endgame, patiently converted, that broke a barrier many thought permanent.</p><div class="tdg-moves"><p class="tdg-moves-title">Full Game</p><pre class="tdg-moves-pre">1.e4 e5 2.Nf3 Nc6 3.Bb5 Nf6 4.O-O Nxe4 5.d4 Nd6 6.Bxc6 dxc6 7.dxe5 Nf5 8.Qxd8+ Kxd8 9.Nc3 h6 10.Rd1+ Ke8 11.h3 Be7 12.Ne2 Nh4 13.Nxh4 Bxh4 14.Be3 Bf5 15.Nd4 Bh7 16.g4 Be7 17.Kg2 h5 18.Nf5 Bf8 19.Kf3 Bg6 20.Rd2 hxg4+ 21.hxg4 Rh3+ 22.Kg2 Rh7 23.Kg3 f6 24.Bf4 Bxf5 25.gxf5 fxe5 26.Re1 Bd6 27.Bxe5 Kd7 28.c4 c5 29.Bxd6 cxd6 30.Re6 Rah8 31.Rexd6+ Kc8 32.R2d5 Rh3+ 33.Kg2 Rh2+ 34.Kf3 R2h3+ 35.Ke4 b6 36.Rc6+ Kb8 37.Rd7 Rh2 38.Ke3 Rf8 39.Rcc7 Rxf5 40.Rb7+ Kc8 41.Rdc7+ Kd8 42.Rxg7 Kc8 1-0</pre></div></article></div></section><section class="tdg-origins" id="tdg-origins"><div class="tdg-gameshead"><span class="tdg-pin">♞</span><h2 class="tdg-localtitle">The Long Road to the 64 Squares</h2><span class="tdg-localtag">History</span></div><p class="tdg-localintro">Long before Morphy and Fischer, before Spain and Italy ever saw a board, the game was born in India and carried west by Persian courts and Arab geographers. A history told from its source, not from Europe.</p><div class="tdg-originsgrid"><div class="tdg-originscol"><p class="tdg-kicker">India · Chaturanga</p><h3 class="tdg-storyhead">A Game Named for an Army</h3><p class="tdg-body">The oldest known ancestor of chess is chaturanga, played in northern India by the sixth and seventh centuries during the Gupta era. Its name is Sanskrit for “having four limbs” — the four divisions of a classical Indian army: infantry, cavalry, elephantry, and chariotry. Those four arms survive on today’s board as the pawn, the knight, the bishop, and the rook. The word itself is older than the game, appearing in the Mahabharata as a term for an army drawn up for battle, and a clear reference to the game by name turns up in Bana’s Harshacharita around 625 AD. Most historians regard chaturanga as the common root not only of chess but of xiangqi in China, shogi in Japan, and makruk in Thailand.</p></div><div class="tdg-originscol"><p class="tdg-kicker">Persia &amp; Arabia · Shatranj</p><h3 class="tdg-storyhead">The Geographer Who Wrote It Down</h3><p class="tdg-body">From India the game travelled to Sassanid Persia, where it became chatrang and entered the education of the nobility; after the Arab conquest, lacking the Persian sounds, the name softened into shatranj. Among those who recorded its story was al-Mas‘udi (c. 896–956), the Baghdad-born historian and traveller later called “the Herodotus of the Arabs.” In his sweeping chronicle The Meadows of Gold he placed the game’s invention squarely in India and gathered the lore around it. It was through this Arabic and Persian world — not a European one — that the game finally crossed into Spain and Sicily, and only then began its long transformation into the chess Morphy would one day master.</p></div></div></section><section class="tdg-local" id="tdg-local">
        <div class="tdg-localhead">
          <span class="tdg-pin">♟</span>
